post_text: May is Mental Health Awareness Month. How often, when someone asks you, ‚Äúhow are you?‚Äù do you respond ‚Äúfine‚Äù without actually thinking about the question? Let‚Äôs dig deeper and figure out how we are ‚Äúreally doing‚Äù. For this week‚Äôs #bhshealthyathome challenge we will join the National How Are You, Really challenge. This is a very difficult time for a lot of people. Even if you are not sharing it on social media, talk to someone in your life about how you are really doing/feeling, and find out how that person is doing as well. During these trying times it is even more important to be connected with loved ones and the community, and to recognize that it is okay to not be okay. ‚ù§Ô∏è #bayheadschool #bayheadsharks #gobayhead

post_text: This week‚Äôs #bhshealthyathome challenge is a water challenge. Did you know that you should drink 8 x 8oz glasses of water per day? Water does so many important jobs in the body, yet it is very common for people to forget about water consumption throughout the day. Replacing fruit juices and soda with water can be an easy first step in achieving better health. For this week‚Äôs challenge, keep track of how much water you drink in a day and try your best to get to that 64 ounce total. If you don‚Äôt like water, try ‚Äúsprucing it up‚Äù a bit by adding fresh fruit or herbs. Mrs. Sierotko grabbed some fresh mint from her herb garden and squeezed a strawberry for some yummy strawberry mint water. Let‚Äôs see your delicious water creations! #bayheadschool #bayheadsharks #bhshealthyathome #gobayhead

post_text: The main components of the Integumentary System includes the skin, hair, nails, and glands. Did you know that the skin is the largest organ in the body? The Integumentary System is often forgotten when people are trying to improve their health, so for this week‚Äôs BHS Healthy at Home Challenge let‚Äôs focus on this body system. Do something to take care of your hair, skin, or nails and share your healthy Integumentary tips with us! Tag us and use #bhshealthyathome Mrs. Sierotko is using a mud mask to take care of her Integumentary System. Mud masks help to bring impurities from deep in the skin to the surface, leaving the pores open and the skin feeling refreshed. Don‚Äôt forget to share your tips with us! #bayheadschool #bayheadsharks #gosharksü¶à

post_text: It‚Äôs time for our next Healthy at Home Challenge! Mental health is such an important part of overall wellness, and yet it often gets overlooked. For this week‚Äôs challenge we are going to practice some mindfulness outside. Find a comfortable spot outside where you can plan to sit for five minutes. During the five minutes, try to pay attention to all five of your senses. What do you hear? What do you see? What do you feel? What do you smell? What do you taste? Pay closer attention to the ant crawling across the ground, or the flower that is blowing with the wind. Focus on being in the moment and try to keep your thoughts solely on what you are experiencing in the present. If you can, have someone snap a picture and post it with #bhshealthyathome but what is most important is that you take this time to complete the challenge for yourself. #bayheadschool #bayheadsharks #bhshealthyathome

post_text: Bay Head Elementary School‚Äôs Kids Heart Challenge event to benefit the American Heart Association is scheduled for February 21st! The Kids Heart Challenge is your child‚Äôs chance to be a Heart Hero by learning about heart health, spreading the word and raising funds to help other children with special hearts. Download the free Kids Heart Challenge mobile app or visit www.heart.org/KidsHeartChallenge to register and have your child take one of three healthy challenges to BE READY, BE KIND OR MOVE MORE. They will receive a free wristband just for registering! Should you choose to email friends and family or post to Facebook for support, your child can earn additional heart hero charms to add to their wristband as well as other thank you gifts. Plus, our school will earn PE equipment and cash incentives! Thank you for supporting students‚Äô physical and emotional well-being and for helping the American Heart Association. Donations are due by February 21st

post_text: After having so much success last year, the Peer Leaders have decided to bring back the Blessing Bag Brigade. As a reminder, the Blessing Bag Brigade is a non-profit organization founded by Kevin Garrison created to show compassion to homeless people in our area by providing them with blessing bags filled with hygiene products, snacks, and socks. We will be collecting items from now until Tuesday, December 3. Last year, many of us asked our Thanksgiving guests to bring requested items to dinner; this gave us a boost shortly after the holiday. Soaps, shampoo, and lotions form hotels are also great donations and many collect them throughout the year. Please see the flyer attached for the list of items we will be collecting.
